dataset_description.json.Name: Fribourg Ultimatum Game in Schizophrenia Study

README:
This is a schizophrenia in ultimatum game task study for Fribourg University. Participants were asked to play the UG in both roles, both as responder and proposer. 128 electrode EEG was recorded during the task. 19 patients with psychosis epoisodes and 24 healths controls were recorded during the task.

This dataset was recorded at the Fribourg University in Switzerland. The project was approved by the Ethics Committee of the University of Fribourg (reference number: 054/13-CER-FR).

Participants sat in a shielded room, in a comfortable chair and played the game, while EEG was recorded. 

For each role, participants performed three blocks, consisting of 30 repetitions each.

sub-027_task-proposer_run-1_eeg.json.TaskDescription: The task is playing the Ultimatum Game. The game involves two players and the goal is to split a certain sum of money between the players (here, 10CHF). The first player (proposer) offers part of the money to the second player (responder).  If responder agrees on the proposed split, both players receive their share of money. If responder refuses the offer, both players get nothing. In this task, the participant is playing as proposer making an offer of money. The player is then provided feedback with a happy or sad face, indicating whether the offer was accepted or not. The responses are computer generated, in a way to emulate human behaviour, with higher acceptance rates of higher offers. The players were not told they are playing against a computer. Each repetition takes 6s beginning with a fixation cross, then the participant makes an offer and receives the response. This is followed by the a 2s rest.

sub-027_task-responder_run-1_eeg.json.TaskDescription: The task is playing the Ultimatum Game. The game involves two players and the goal is to split a certain sum of money between the players (here, 10CHF). The first player (proposer) offers part of the money to the second player (responder).  If responder agrees on the proposed split, both players receive their share of money. If responder refuses the offer, both players get nothing. In this task, the participant is playing as responder, making decisions to refuse or accept the offer. The offers are made by the computer and are randomly drawn from a normal distribution centred around 3CHF. The players were not told they are playing against a computer. Each repetition takes 6s beginning with a fixation cross, then the offer is presented and the participant makes a decision. This is followed by the a 2s rest.
